25|$|The Great Whirl {{is a huge}} anti-cyclonic eddy {{generated}} by the Somali current flowing in (northern) summer, {{and one of the}} two gigantic Indian Ocean Gyres (the other is the Socotra Gyre). The Great Whirl can be observed between 5-10°N and 52-57°E off the Somali coast in the summer season, a location typically around 200km southwest of the Socotra Gyre (between June to September). However, in the past both the Great Whirl and the Socotra Gyre have been known to occasionally collapse, and their exact locations differ from year to year. The Great Whirl's typical size is 400–600km in horizontal diameter, and typical <b>surface</b> <b>current</b> velocity is 1.5-2.0m/s.|$|E
